&gt; swayed.
&gt; &gt; Really, I would.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; I would think that many would see the Luminator efforts as a
&gt; modern
&gt; &gt; &gt; effort at scrying.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Do you mean scrying as in the psychomanteum method developed by
&gt; &gt; Raymond Moody? My understanding, from attending a presentation by
&gt; Dr.
&gt; &gt; Moody, was that the psychomanteum produced full-blown apparitions
&gt; &gt; that could converse with the bereaved. Not sure these two types of
&gt; &gt; events are comparable.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Everything we do crosses boundaries, and my point is that it&#39;s
&gt; &gt; &gt; really hard to walk the line between trying to be scientific and
&gt; &gt; &gt; trying to be open. It&#39;s really, really hard! But if we give in
&gt; one
&gt; &gt; &gt; area, we have to be willing to give in another.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I don&#39;t think that is arguably true, Ursula. If the evidence
&gt; appears
&gt; &gt; good, I acknowledge it; if the evidence appears weak, I
&gt; acknowledge
&gt; &gt; it. It is simply not true to say that a person cannot be both open-
&gt; &gt; minded and scientific. I really do want to believe, but I won&#39;t
&gt; &gt; believe just because I want to. And because you, me, or anyone
&gt; &gt; &quot;gives&quot; in one area, does not make a phenomenon any more or less
&gt; real.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Your fellow traveler on this journey,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Ann
